without the permission or presence of the parents -- if the goal is to check that the child is being educated. That was my point. &#10;No, I'm sorry, I don't agree entirely. The ultimate responsibility for the wellbeing of the child is not the state's -- it's the parents. The state should only step in if they can show that the parents are abusing or neglecting the child. &#10;The distinction is a subtle one in this case, because abuse or neglect is what you and I are discussing. But it's important: I don't believe that the state has the right to demand that I teach my child according to their curriculum, for example. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="916" language="en" documentId="951" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Shadowfirebird" date="06 November 2009 6:19pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6747362" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="1" thumbsDown="0" origId="951" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="12"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="13" end="205"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="206" end="429"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="430" end="669"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="670" end="916"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55"/></xmi:XMI>